The `BIGINT` data type is an *8-byte binary number*, which means that the matching Java type is a **`long`**, so use [`getLong()`][1]:

```lang-java
long mob = rs.getLong(&quot;emp_mob&quot;);
```

If the column is `NULL`-able, use Java type **`Long`**, and call [`wasNull()`][2] after calling `getLong()`:

```lang-java
Long mob = rs.getLong(&quot;emp_mob&quot;);
if (rs.wasNull())
    mob = null;
```

Alternatively, if you want a Java [**`BigInteger`**][3], call [`getBigDecimal()`][4] and convert it:

```lang-java
BigDecimal decimal = rs.getBigDecimal(&quot;emp_mob&quot;);
BigInteger mob = (decimal == null ? null : decimal.toBigInteger());
```


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/ResultSet.html#getLong-java.lang.String-
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/ResultSet.html#wasNull--
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/math/BigInteger.html
